n be significant. I realize that while Circe's `JsonObject` preserves insertion order, there aren't existing tests for it. It’s critical for deterministic rendering, so I want to explore whether we can test the source object field ordering effectively.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Adding tests for array order**\\n\\nI realize the existing system only covers static counts for array order. However, it doesn't account for mixed interpolated arrays. I think I can introduce a test that checks both object order and array order when using dynamic values and keys. I wonder if I should re-test key encoders or if I can just use String keys, since dynamic key uses `KeyEncoder[String]`, which is already covered. My focus is on ensuring that both dynamic and static fields maintain their order.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_EMFX5oPvDn2mgZ41nyr8yzS9|fc_0ea86fb99aebd01c016a3ffe2d525081939a26f7cfdecf7a7d", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "javap -classpath ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/io.circe/circe-literal_3/0.14.15/dc03776ed359ebb723a858eb35a37a560f304066/circe-literal_3-0.14.15.jar -c -p io.circe.literal.Replacement | sed -n '1,280p'", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 702, "output": 970, "cacheRead": 49152, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 50824, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782578718711, "responseId": "resp_0ea86fb99aebd01c016a3ffe1f4af081939cc729ed7c8fcb8b"}}
